    <title>Combined summary - Proposal: Bundled payments</title>
    <updated>2023-07-05T02:56:17.858093+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/lightning-dev/2023-June/003977.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Thomas Voegtlin has proposed extending BOLT-11, the Lightning Network protocol, to allow invoices containing two bundled payments with distinct preimages and amounts. This proposal is targeted at services that require a prepayment of a mining fee for non-custodial exchanges like submarine swaps and JIT (Just-in-Time) channels. The objective is to level the competition between lightning service providers and address vulnerabilities such as the mining fee attack.The proposal suggests implementing this feature in BOLT-12 rather than updating BOLT-11. Thomas argues that since existing software used by senders still relies on 0-conf (zero-confirmation transactions), it would make more sense to include the new feature in Bolt 12. However, there are ongoing discussions about the implementation and concerns about introducing another incompatible version of BOLT-11.Matt Corallo expresses skepticism about introducing new interoperable changes to BOLT-11 and recommends focusing on a "standard" way of doing swaps built on Onion Messages (OMs) to enhance privacy. He believes that expecting widespread support for yet another version of BOLT-11 may not be feasible.In response to questions about splice-outs and submarine swaps, it is explained that submarine swaps enable the addition of receiving capacity to a channel. The suggestion is made to establish a "standard" way of doing swaps using OMs for better privacy.There is also discussion about whether the proposed feature should be required or optional for service providers. Dave suggests extending BOLT-11 invoices with an extra_fee_via_keysend field to save space for the prepayment hash, allowing immediate implementation until an updated version of BOLT-11 or an alternative using offers becomes widely deployed. Thomas responds positively to this idea, noting that it would indeed save space for the prepayment hash.The overall aim of Thomas's proposal is to enhance BOLT-11 by allowing invoices to contain two bundled payments. This extension would cater to the needs of services that require prepayment of a mining fee, such as submarine swaps and JIT channels. The proposed semantics involve waiting for the arrival of all HTLCs (Hash Time-Locked Contracts) for both payments before fulfilling the HTLCs of the prepayment. The decision to make this feature required or optional remains with the service provider.While there is interest in finding a more satisfying solution for bundled payments, there are concerns about the feasibility and compatibility of implementing this feature in BOLT-11. It may be more practical to explore options within BOLT-12 or other protocols to achieve the desired functionality.</summary>
